  <!-- NEW: Paradigm Shift Introduction -->
  <section class="py-8 bg-amber-50 border-b border-amber-200">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="key-concept">
        <div class="key-concept-title">üîÑ A New Perspective on Gangliosides</div>
        <p class="mb-3">
          Traditional ganglioside research focuses on <em>pathology</em>: "GT1b is a receptor for tetanus toxin," 
          "GM2 accumulation causes Tay-Sachs." But this begs the question: <strong>Why do neurons invest so 
          heavily in this complex system?</strong>
        </p>
        <p class="mb-0">
          This page explores the <strong>physiological function</strong> of gangliosides ‚Äî proposing that they 
          form an "operating system" for neuronal communication, with electrostatic properties that enable 
          sophisticated filtering of signals by time, distance, and source.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Introduction -->
  <section class="py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose-science">
        <h2>What are Gangliosides?</h2>
        <p>
          Gangliosides are complex sphingolipids containing one or more sialic acid residues. 
          They are abundant in the nervous system, comprising <strong>10-12% of total lipid content</strong> in 
          neuronal membranes ‚Äî an enormous metabolic investment that hints at fundamental importance.
        </p>
        
        <div class="info-box">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">üí° The Central Question</h4>
          <p class="text-blue-700 text-sm mb-0">
            Each sialic acid residue carries a <strong>negative charge</strong>. Why would neurons coat 
            themselves and their vesicles with densely charged molecules? The answer, we propose, lies 
            in <strong>electrostatic signaling</strong> ‚Äî using charge as a communication medium.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="key-concept">
          <div class="key-concept-title">Key Concept: GT1b Ganglioside</div>
          <p class="mb-0">
            GT1b is a trisialoganglioside with <strong>three sialic acids</strong> ‚Äî giving it a strong 
            negative charge. It serves as the primary receptor for tetanus toxin and enables 
            retrograde axonal transport. We propose GT1b is part of a larger <strong>neurotrophin 
            transport highway</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <h2>The Svennerholm Classification</h2>
        <p>
          Gangliosides are classified using the Svennerholm nomenclature system, where:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>G</strong> = Ganglioside</li>
          <li><strong>M, D, T, Q</strong> = Number of sialic acid residues (Mono, Di, Tri, Quadra)</li>
          <li><strong>1, 2, 3</strong> = Order of migration on chromatography</li>
          <li><strong>a, b, c</strong> = Position of sialic acids on the sugar chain</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>A-Series vs B-Series: Critical Differences</h2>
        <p>
          The distinction between a-series (monosialo) and b-series (disialo) gangliosides is 
          <strong>central to understanding the hypothesis</strong>. These series differ fundamentally 
          in their behavior, localization, and clinical significance.
        </p>

        <table class="w-full text-sm my-6">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b bg-slate-50">
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">Property</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">A-Series (Monosialo)</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">B-Series (Disialo)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Examples</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">GM3 ‚Üí GM2 ‚Üí GM1 ‚Üí GD1a</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">GD3 ‚Üí GD2 ‚Üí GD1b ‚Üí GT1b ‚Üí GQ1b</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Key enzyme</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">ST3GAL5 (GM3 synthase)</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">ST8SIA1 (GD3 synthase)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Membrane behavior</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Stable in lipid rafts</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Dynamic, prone to export</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Primary location</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Nodes of Ranvier, myelin</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Synaptic terminals, oculomotor nerves</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Shedding rate</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-green-600">Low</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-amber-600 font-bold">High</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Storage diseases</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">GM1/GM2 gangliosidosis</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-amber-600 font-bold">None known!</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b bg-red-50">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-medium">Immune exposure</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Lower</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-red-600 font-bold">Higher (Miller Fisher, GBS)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="key-concept">
          <div class="key-concept-title">The Shedding Mechanism</div>
          <p>
            B-series gangliosides (GD3, GT1b, GQ1b) have a <strong>higher negative charge</strong> 
            due to their two sialic acid residues. This promotes export via extracellular vesicles 
            (EVs/exosomes) through ceramide-dependent budding. This "bypass" of lysosomal 
            degradation has two critical consequences:
          </p>
          <ol class="mt-2 mb-0">
            <li><strong>No lysosomal accumulation</strong> ‚Üí No storage disease phenotype</li>
            <li><strong>Increased extracellular exposure</strong> ‚Üí Higher vulnerability to autoimmune attack</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Illustration: A-series vs B-series -->
        <figure class="my-8">
          <img 
            src="/images/intracellular-storage-extracellular-shedding.png" 
            alt="A-series (GM1) leads to intracellular storage in lysosomes, while B-series (GT1b) is exported via exosomes for extracellular communication"
            class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 shadow-lg"
          />
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-3 text-center">
            <strong>The Great Divide:</strong> A-series gangliosides (GM1) are directed to lysosomes 
            for degradation ‚Äî a "dead end" that causes storage diseases when blocked. B-series 
            gangliosides (GT1b) are exported via exosomes for intercellular communication ‚Äî 
            bypassing lysosomal accumulation but increasing immune exposure.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>Clinical Evidence: Miller Fisher Syndrome</h3>
        <p>
          Miller Fisher syndrome (MFS) perfectly illustrates the b-series vulnerability. This 
          variant of Guillain-Barr√© syndrome is characterized by:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Clinical triad:</strong> Ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, areflexia</li>
          <li><strong>Anti-GQ1b antibodies:</strong> Present in 85-90% of cases</li>
          <li><strong>Post-infectious trigger:</strong> Often <em>Campylobacter jejuni</em></li>
          <li><strong>Molecular mimicry:</strong> Bacterial lipo-oligosaccharides resemble GQ1b epitopes</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="warning-box">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800 mb-2">Why Oculomotor Nerves?</h4>
          <p class="text-amber-700 text-sm mb-0">
            The oculomotor nerves and dorsal root ganglia are <strong>enriched in b-series gangliosides</strong> 
            (GT1b, GQ1b). Their high shedding rate increases local immune exposure, explaining the 
            selective vulnerability in MFS. The same mechanism may apply to orexin neurons in 
            post-Pandemrix narcolepsy.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-box mt-6">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">A-Series (GM3) and the Auditory System</h4>
          <p class="text-blue-700 text-sm mb-2">
            GM3 is essential for cochlear function ‚Äî GM3 synthase deficiency causes profound deafness. 
            We explored whether H3N2 influenza (which binds GM3) could explain "Havana Syndrome" via 
            similar ganglioside-mediated mechanisms.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-0">
            <strong class="text-red-600">Result:</strong> After critical evaluation, this hypothesis was found 
            <strong>unlikely</strong>. See: <a href="/speculation/havana-syndrome/" class="text-red-600 underline">The Havana Hypothesis (Falsified)</a>
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- NEW: Ganglioside Degradation Section -->
        <h2 class="mt-12">Ganglioside Degradation: The Four Mammalian Neuraminidases</h2>
        <p>
          Understanding ganglioside <strong>degradation</strong> is just as important as understanding biosynthesis. 
          Four mammalian neuraminidases (NEU1‚ÄìNEU4) are responsible for removing sialic acids from gangliosides 
          and glycoproteins ‚Äî but they differ dramatically in their <strong>substrate specificity</strong>, 
          <strong>subcellular localization</strong>, and <strong>physiological roles</strong>.
        </p>

        <div class="key-concept">
          <div class="key-concept-title">Why Does This Matter?</div>
          <p class="mb-0">
            Understanding which neuraminidase acts on which ganglioside is critical for the narcolepsy hypothesis. 
            For example, <strong>NEU1</strong> (often discussed in genetic studies) has <strong>minimal activity 
            against gangliosides like GT1b</strong> ‚Äî it primarily acts on N-glycans. If ganglioside accumulation 
            is relevant to NT1, we must look at <strong>NEU3 or NEU4</strong> instead.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h3>The Four Neuraminidases: A Comparison</h3>
        <table class="w-full text-sm my-6">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b bg-slate-50">
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">Enzyme</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">Location</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">Primary Substrates</th>
              <th class="text-left py-2 px-2">Ganglioside Activity</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b bg-cyan-50">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-bold text-cyan-800">NEU1</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Lysosomal</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Oligosaccharides, N-glycans (glycoproteins)</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-red-600 font-bold">Very low / minimal</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-bold text-slate-700">NEU2</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Cytosolic</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Broad (in vitro), unclear physiologically</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-amber-600">Moderate (but cytosolic location limits access)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b bg-green-50">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-bold text-green-800">NEU3</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Plasma membrane</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Gangliosides (GM3 ‚Üí lactosylceramide, etc.)</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-green-600 font-bold">Highest specificity!</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b bg-purple-50">
              <td class="py-2 px-2 font-bold text-purple-800">NEU4</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Lysosomal / Mitochondrial / ER</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2">Gangliosides, glycoproteins, oligosaccharides (broad)</td>
              <td class="py-2 px-2 text-purple-600 font-bold">High (broad specificity)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
          <div class="bg-cyan-50 border border-cyan-200 rounded-lg p-4">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-cyan-800 mb-2">NEU1 ‚Äî The "Glycoprotein Sialidase"</h4>
            <ul class="text-cyan-700 text-sm space-y-1">
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Location:</strong> Lysosome (forms complex with Cathepsin A and Œ≤-galactosidase)</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Substrates:</strong> Œ±2,3- and Œ±2,6-linked sialic acids on oligosaccharides and glycoproteins</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Gangliosides:</strong> <span class="text-red-600 font-bold">Minimal activity</span> ‚Äî does NOT efficiently hydrolyze gangliosides</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Deficiency:</strong> Causes Sialidosis (accumulation of sialylated oligosaccharides, NOT gangliosides)</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-cyan-600 text-xs mt-2 italic">
              ‚ö†Ô∏è NEU1 is often mentioned in narcolepsy genetics due to its MHC location, but it does NOT act on GT1b.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-green-800 mb-2">NEU3 ‚Äî The "Ganglioside Specialist"</h4>
            <ul class="text-green-700 text-sm space-y-1">
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Location:</strong> Plasma membrane (cell surface and inner leaflet)</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Substrates:</strong> Gangliosides ‚Äî requires hydrophobic aglycon</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Key reaction:</strong> GM3 ‚Üí lactosylceramide (and similar)</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Role:</strong> Primary enzyme for ganglioside desialylation at cell surface</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-green-600 text-xs mt-2 italic">
              ‚úì If ganglioside accumulation is relevant to NT1, NEU3 (Chr 11q13) is a better candidate than NEU1.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
          <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-800 mb-2">NEU2 ‚Äî The "Cytosolic Enigma"</h4>
            <ul class="text-slate-700 text-sm space-y-1">
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Location:</strong> Cytosol (no membrane association)</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>In vitro:</strong> Broad specificity including some gangliosides</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>In vivo:</strong> Physiological role unclear ‚Äî cytosolic location limits access to membrane lipids</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Note:</strong> Some species (fish) lack NEU2 ortholog entirely</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-purple-50 border border-purple-200 rounded-lg p-4">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-purple-800 mb-2">NEU4 ‚Äî The "Lysosomal Backup"</h4>
            <ul class="text-purple-700 text-sm space-y-1">
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Location:</strong> Lysosomal lumen, mitochondria, ER</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Substrates:</strong> Broad ‚Äî gangliosides (GD1a, GM1, GM2), glycoproteins, oligosaccharides</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Role:</strong> Contributes to lysosomal ganglioside catabolism</li>
              <li>‚Ä¢ <strong>Key finding:</strong> NEU4 overexpression rescues sialidosis cells (complements NEU1 deficiency)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="warning-box">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800 mb-2">‚ö†Ô∏è Critical Point for Narcolepsy Hypothesis</h4>
          <p class="text-amber-700 text-sm mb-2">
            <strong>NEU1</strong> lies in the MHC region (6p21.33) near HLA-DQB1*06:02 and is often discussed 
            as a candidate gene. However, NEU1 has <strong>minimal activity against gangliosides like GT1b</strong>.
          </p>
          <p class="text-amber-700 text-sm mb-0">
            If ganglioside metabolism is relevant to narcolepsy pathogenesis, the relevant enzymes would be 
            <strong>NEU3</strong> (11q13.5) or <strong>NEU4</strong> (2q37.3) ‚Äî which are NOT in linkage disequilibrium 
            with the HLA risk haplotype. This is an important distinction.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h3>The Extracellular "Vesicle Clock"</h3>
        <p>
          One fascinating aspect of ganglioside biology is that neuraminidases also exist in the 
          <strong>extracellular space</strong>. These extracellular sialidases progressively strip sialic 
          acids from vesicles as they travel through the nervous system, creating a "biological clock" that 
          encodes time and distance.
        </p>

        <div class="info-box">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">The "Vesicle Clock" Concept</h4>
          <p class="text-blue-700 text-sm mb-0">
            As a GT1b-rich vesicle travels, extracellular neuraminidases progressively convert it: 
            GT1b ‚Üí GD1b ‚Üí GM1 ‚Üí asialo-GM1. This gradual "stripping" creates a time/distance signature 
            that receiving neurons can read ‚Äî enabling sophisticated filtering of signals by source and age.
          </p>
        </div>

