      <div class="prose-science">
        
        <!-- PART 1: THE GT1B TRANSPORT SYSTEM -->
        <h2>Why B-Series Gangliosides Are Special</h2>
        <p>
          The distinction between A-series and B-series gangliosides isn't just biochemistry ‚Äî 
          it's the key to understanding how substances travel through the nervous system. 
          Let's build this understanding step by step.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 1: The GT1b Paradox ‚Äî No Storage Disease</h3>
        <p>
          Here's a puzzle: most gangliosides cause devastating storage diseases when they accumulate 
          (GM1 gangliosidosis, Tay-Sachs for GM2). Yet <strong>there is no known disease caused by 
          GT1b or GD1b accumulation</strong>. Why?
        </p>
        
        <p>
          The answer reveals something fundamental: <strong>B-series gangliosides are exported, 
          not stored</strong>. When GT1b levels rise, the excess is released via extracellular 
          vesicles (exosomes) ‚Äî a "bypass" of normal lysosomal degradation.
        </p>

        <!-- Key Illustration: Cholera vs Tetanus Transport -->
        <figure class="my-8">
          <img 
            src="/images/choleratoxin-tetanus-toxin-transport.jpg" 
            alt="Cholera toxin (GM1) stays intracellular targeting Golgi, while Tetanus toxin (GT1b) is released via signaling endosomes for trans-synaptic jump"
            class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 shadow-lg"
          />
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-3 text-center">
            <strong>Two Toxins, Two Fates:</strong> Cholera toxin (binding GM1) remains intracellular. 
            Tetanus toxin (binding GT1b) is released and makes a <em>trans-synaptic jump</em>. 
            This is why GT1b-bound substances spread through neural circuits.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>Step 2: The Electrostatic Explanation</h3>
        <p>
          Why does B-series get exported while A-series gets stored? The answer lies in 
          <strong>electrical charge</strong>.
        </p>

        <!-- Electrostatic Transport Illustration -->
        <figure class="my-8">
          <img 
            src="/images/electrostatic-vesicle-transport.svg" 
            alt="Electrostatic vesicle transport showing how negative charges on GT1b-rich vesicles enable 'gliding' through the nervous system while specific receptors enable targeted delivery"
            class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 shadow-lg bg-white"
          />
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-slate-600 mt-3 text-center">
            <strong>The "Slippery Soap" Mechanism:</strong> Both vesicles and cell surfaces are negatively charged. 
            This repulsion prevents random adhesion ‚Äî the vesicle "glides" through the extracellular space. 
            Delivery occurs only when specific receptor binding overcomes the electrostatic barrier.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-4">‚ö° The Physics of Ganglioside Transport</h4>
          
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-4">
            <div class="bg-white rounded p-4 border border-blue-200">
              <h5 class="font-bold text-blue-700 mb-2">Sialic Acid = Negative Charge</h5>
              <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
                Each sialic acid residue carries a <strong>negative charge</strong> at physiological pH.
              </p>
              <ul class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-1 ml-4 list-disc">
                <li>GM1 (A-series): 1 sialic acid ‚Üí <span class="text-slate-500">low charge</span></li>
                <li>GT1b (B-series): 3 sialic acids ‚Üí <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold">high charge</span></li>
                <li>GQ1b (B-series): 4 sialic acids ‚Üí <span class="text-blue-700 font-bold">very high charge</span></li>
